Cure ballot
Ballot curing is the process of a ballot not getting counted
because of an error such as a mismatching signature
(which can be an honest mistake), and then the voter has
an opportunity to affirm that they intended to vote and
want their vote counted. They get to "cure" their rejected
ballot.

Campaigns are able to get a list of voters whose ballots
were rejected to help reach out to them and urge them to
"cure" their ballot and make sure it gets counted.
In order to "cure" a ballot, the registered voter has to
confirm they intended to and did vote — which means any
votes by people who don't exist don't get cured and
counted.
