Ink outside signature box
There is no specific rule in California elections stating that
if ink goes outside the signature rectangle on a ballot or
form, the signature or the entire sheet automatically
becomes invalid. However, California election officials do
review signatures carefully to verify voter identity, and
significant discrepancies or issues with the signature
could lead to a ballot being rejected.
Minor ink marks outside the signature box alone are
unlikely to invalidate a ballot unless they interfere with
signature verification.
