Thanks for reaching out you’re right that some
misinformation is being spread about the Voter ID
Initiative, and it’s important we clear it up with the facts
straight from the measure itself.
The initiative simply amends the California Constitution to
require proof of identity when voting either showing a
government issued ID at the polls or providing the last
four digits of your ID number when voting by mail. It does
not make voting harder or add any new paperwork for
eligible voters.
If the name on a voter’s ID doesn’t match what’s on the
voter rolls (for example, a maiden vs. married name), they

can simply update their registration to match their legal
name the same as when someone moves or changes their
address today.
Also, no one will be turned away for not having a license.
The initiative guarantees:
“Government-issued identification means documentation
that allows conclusive verification of the voter’s identity.
Upon request by an eligible voter, the state shall provide,
at no charge, a voter ID card for use in casting a ballot.”
That means any eligible voter can get a free voter ID
card from the state. Not to mention a license is not the
only form of ID, other valid forms of government-issued ID
can include passport, military ID, state ID, SSN which will
all also qualify.
The government issued ID of your choosing will be used
solely to confirm a voter’s identity when voting. For mail
ballots, voters would just write the last four digits of their
ID number on the envelope to confirm their identity.
Anyone claiming this initiative “makes voting harder” is
simply trying to undermine confidence in fair elections
and mislead voters. The measure makes our
system stronger and more transparent, ensuring every
eligible voter can easily cast a secure ballot.
You can find this exact language in Section 3.1(a) and
3.1(b) of the initiative text >>
